	*** Summary
	    The authors present Google File System (GFS), a distributed file system
	    which provides fault tolerance with inexpensive hardware and can be scale
	    to a large number of client while delivering high aggregate performance.
	    GFS is designed with four key insights: 1) failure is normal, 2) files can
	    be large, 3) appeding is the most frequent mutating operation, and 4)
	    co-designing the applications and file system API can be beneficial.
	
	*** Review Questions
	    1. Comparing with AFS, which system offers more reliability, AFS or GFS?
	       - GFS should be more reliable as it provides multiple replication on the
	         the server/master-end. Hence the tasks can be balanced to other
	         replications if one the server/master is down.
	
