	In this project, the team proposes a resource manager that can understand the
	applications and make decision based on the understand. This understanding is
	achieved based on a key insight --- applications will have different magnitudes
	of performance improvement/degradation toward the change in the amount of
	resource available depending on the input data and how much resource the
	applications currently have, which we defined as applications' sensitivities.
	The resource manager framework can be divided into three major parts. First,
	there is a control layer where the resource manager limits the amount of
	resource exposed to the edge devices/applications. For example, the control
	layer uses Linux tc to control the network traffic between the devices and
	central servers, and a token-based time-slicing GPU scheduler to limit the GPU
	computing resource available to the applications. Second, there is a
	communication layer where, together with the control layer, the resource
	manager periodically profile and query the sensitivities from the applications.
	Finally, the sensitivities will be passed to a decision making layer which is
	responisble to change resource allocation to optimize the overall performance
	(e.g., maximize throughput, minimize latency, et al.) based on applications
	sensitivities.
